15 DUTIES OF THE BOARD
16
17 SECTION 6. Minimum workforce standards. (1) Subject to subsections (4), (5) and (6) of
18 this section, the Home and Community-Based Services Workforce Standards Board shall
19 adopt rules establishing minimum standards for the home and community-based services
20 workforce that are designed to improve the working conditions of such workers and that
21 may be tailored to specific categories of worker types and across different care settings. The
22 board may not adopt any standards that:
23 (a) Are less protective of or beneficial to the home and community-based services
24 workforce than the standards provided under any other applicable statute or rule; or
25 (b) Infringe on an individual’s right to self-determination, as defined in ORS 427.101.
26 (2) At a minimum, the standards must:
27 (a) Set compensation rates for paying individuals in the home and community-based
28 services workforce, provided that the rates are not less than the minimum wage rate es-
29 tablished under ORS 653.025.
30 (b) Establish curriculum and criteria for providing education and professional develop-
31 ment opportunities and career pathways for the home and community-based services
32 workforce.
33 (c) Provide for the provision of health care benefits and other paid benefits for the home
34 and community-based services workforce, including but not limited to paid family leave, sick
35 leave and retirement benefits.
36 (3) Before establishing any minimum standards under this section, the board shall:
37 (a) Obtain and evaluate the following information in relation to the home and
38 community-based services workforce to ensure that the standards adopted by the board meet
39 or exceed prevailing labor market conditions:
40 (A) Labor market data, including but not limited to:
41 (i) Wage levels and benefit data from comparable occupations and industries within dif-
42 ferent geographic regions in this state;
43 (ii) Collective bargaining agreements applicable to workers in comparable occupations
44 and industries within different geographic regions in this state; and
45 (iii) Existing federal, state and local minimum standards for the home and community-
[5]

