31 BOARD AUTHORITY
32
33 SECTION 9. Investigative authority. In order to determine any facts relevant to matters
34 concerning implementation of and compliance with the minimum standards established by
35 the Home and Community-Based Services Workforce Standards Board under section 6 of this
36 2026 Act, the Commissioner of the Bureau of Labor and Industries may conduct investi-
37 gations, issue subpoenas and subpoenas duces tecum, administer oaths, obtain evidence and
38 take testimony to the same extent that the commissioner may exercise such authority with
39 respect to the bureau’s duties as described under ORS 651.060.
40
41 WORKER PROTECTIONS
42
43 SECTION 10. Retaliation prohibited. It is an unlawful practice under ORS chapter 659A
44 for an employer to terminate, discipline, penalize, retaliate or take any other adverse action
45 against any worker from the home and community-based services workforce because the
[8]

SB 1505
1 worker has:
2 (1) Inquired about or exercised any right afforded to a worker under sections 1 to 13 of
3 this 2026 Act or under any minimum standards established by the board under section 6 of
4 this 2026 Act.
5 (2) Participated in any process or proceeding under or related to sections 1 to 13 of this
6 2026 Act, or has testified or is about to testify in any such proceeding.
7 SECTION 11. Remedies. (1) No sooner than 90 days after a rule establishing a minimum
8 standard under section 6 of this 2026 Act takes effect, a worker from the home and
9 community-based services workforce or a labor organization may seek relief for an alleged
10 violation of a minimum standard established by the Home and Community-Based Services
11 Workforce Standards Board under section 6 of this 2026 Act by:
12 (a) Commencing a civil action in the circuit court of appropriate jurisdiction for
13 injunctive relief, damages or other appropriate equitable relief against any person alleged to
14 have violated a minimum standard; or
15 (b) Filing a complaint with the Commissioner of the Bureau of Labor and Industries in
16 the manner provided by ORS 659A.820, not later than one year after the date of the alleged
17 violation. In addition to any other penalty provided by law, the Commissioner of the Bureau
18 of Labor and Industries may assess a civil penalty under ORS 183.745 not to exceed $1,000 for
19 each violation of a minimum standard adopted by the board under section 6 of this 2026 Act.
20 (2) Prior to commencing a civil action under subsection (1)(a) of this section, the person
21 alleging the violation shall provide written notice to the person alleged to have violated the
22 minimum standard stating that the person shall have 30 days from receipt of the notice to
23 correct the alleged violation. A civil action may not be brought against the person alleged
24 to have violated the minimum standard if the person has corrected the alleged violation
25 within the time period specified under this subsection.
26 (3) A labor organization may file a civil action under this section only on behalf of
27 workers from the home and community-based services workforce whom the labor organiza-
28 tion represents. A labor organization may not file a civil action on behalf of workers who are
29 not represented by the labor organization.
30 (4) Upon prevailing in an action under this section, the plaintiff may recover actual
31 damages and the court shall award reasonable attorney fees and costs to the prevailing
32 plaintiff.
33 SECTION 12. Limits. Nothing in sections 1 to 13 of this 2026 Act is intended to:
34 (1) Limit, interfere with or reduce the rights of any parties to a collective bargaining
35 agreement.
36 (2) Diminish the rights or remedies that are otherwise available to a worker from the
37 home and community-based services workforce under federal or state law or regulation, in-
38 cluding but not limited to the right to file a wage claim under ORS 652.310 to 652.414.
39 SECTION 13. Employer notice requirements. (1) Each employer of workers of the home
40 and community-based services workforce shall provide notice to the workers of the following:
41 (a) The rights of the workers with respect to the minimum standards established by the
42 Home and Community-Based Services Workforce Standards Board under section 6 of this
43 2026 Act.
44 (b) The duties and functions of the board.
45 (c) Contact information for each state agency responsible with enforcement authority
[9]

SB 1505
1 over matters that relate to the same subjects over which the board has authority.
2 (2) The employer shall provide the notice required under this section as follows:
3 (a) At the time of hire;
4 (b) In the same language that the employer typically communicates with the worker;
5 (c) By posting the notice in a conspicuous location in the workplace; and
6 (d) By sending the notice to the electronic mail address of each worker of the employer.
7 (3) The board shall annually review and update the notice required under this section
8 insofar as necessary to reflect changes to any minimum standards that are adopted by the
9 board.
